esident]] in the [[2012 United States presidential election|2012 general election]], was held May 2\u20136, 2012 in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]] at the [[Red Rock Resort Spa and Casino]].<ref name=myers>Myers, Laura (November 30, 2010) [http://www.lvrj.com/news/las-vegas-will-host-libertarian-convention-111027874.html \"Las Vegas will host Libertarian convention\"], ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]''. Retrieved November 30, 2010.</ref><ref name=malcolm>Malcolm, Andrew (November 30, 2010) [http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/washington/2010/11/las-vegas-libertarian-party.html \"Las Vegas gets its first national political convention\"], ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''. Retrieved November 30, 2010.</ref> Former [[Governor of New Mexico]] [[Gary Johnson]] won the presidential nomination on the first ballot.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/05/06/us-usa-libertarians-idUSBRE8440BZ20120506 | title=Libertarians nominate ex-Governor Gary Johnson for president | work=[[Reuters]] | date=May 5, 2012 | accessdate=May 6, 2012 | author=Pratt, Timothy}}</ref> Retired [[Superior Courts of California|California state court]] judge [[James P. Gray|Jim Gray]] won the vice presidential nomination, also on the first ballot.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.uncoveredpolitics.com/2012/05/05/libertarians-nominate-judge-jim-gray-for-vice-president/ | title=Libertarians Nominate Judge Jim Gray for Vice-President | work=Uncovered Politics | date=May 5, 2012 | accessdate=May 6, 2012 | author=Cassidy, Austin}}</ref> The convention also chose to replace most of the [[Libertarian National Committee]] party officers and members-at-large.\n\nThe theme<!--Libertarian Party national conventions regularly have themes.  For example,  themes in 2016, 2014, 2010, 2008, 2006, 2004, 2002, 2000, 1998, and 1996 were \"#LegalizeFreedom\", \"Character Matters\", \"Gateway to Liberty\", \"A Better Choice for America\", \"Uniting Voters\", \"Liberty Works\", \"Champions of Liberty\", \"America's Future: Liberty, Responsibility & Community\", \"Road to Victory\", and \"Declare Your Independence\" respectively.--> of this convention was ''Liberty Will Win''.<ref name=\"Convention Website\">{{cite web|url=http://www.libertywillwin.com/ |title=Welcome to 2012 Libertarian National Convention |date=May 9, 2012 |website=Web.archive.org |accessdate=June 25, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509083125/http://www.libertywillwin.com/ |archivedate=May 9, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Host selection==\nThis was the first presidential nominating convention ever held in the Las Vegas Valley.<ref name=myers/><ref name=malcolm/><ref name=winger>[[Richard Winger|Winger, Richard]] (November 21, 2010) [http://www.ballot-access.org/2010/11/21/libertarian-presidential-convention-will-be-may-4-6-2012-in-las-vegas/ \"Libertarian Presidential Convention Will be May 4\u20136, 2012, in Las Vegas\"], ''[[Ballot Access News]]''. Retrieved December 1, 2010.</ref> Other cities that bid to host the convention included [[Dallas|Dallas, Texas]] and [[San Francisco|San Francisco, California]].<ref name=winger/>\n\n==Candidates debate==\nIn February 2012, [[Gary Johnson]], [[Lee Wrights]], Bill Still, [[Carl Person]], and Leroy Saunders participated in a debate held by the [[Libertarian Party of Florida]] and moderated by LPUSA Chair [[Mark Hinkle]].{{citation needed|date=May 2012}}\nThe debate participants were selected by convention delegates in a secret ballot, in which a candidate needed to score 10 percent of the vote or higher to be allowed to take part. Libertarian candidates in the debate called for ending government interference in personal, family and business decisions; much lower government spending; deregulation; lower taxes; a currency free of government manipulation; free trade; and a peaceful, [[non-interventionism|non-interventionist foreign policy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lpgeorgia.com/blog/libertarian-national-convention-chooses-presidential-debaters/|title=Libertarian National Convention Chooses Presidential Debaters|website=Lpgeorgia.com|accessdate=June 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Schedule==\nThe convention covered five days over May 2\u20136. The business of deciding the national platform and candidates formally began on May 3, and a second candidate debate was held on May 4. On May 5, the party nominated Gary Johnson as its presidential candidate and Jim Gray as vice presidential candidate. On May 6, elections for the Libertarian National Committee concluded.<ref>{{cite web |title=2012 Convention Schedule |url=http://www.libertywillwin.com/node/3 |accessdate=26 September 2012 |author=Libertarian National Committee |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120624030440/http://www.libertywillwin.com/node/3 |archivedate=June 24, 2012 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nCandidates for the presidential nomination were required to gather \"tokens\" from delegates. 53 tokens were required to participate in debates, while 30 were needed to be listed on the ballot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.independentpoliticalreport.com/2012/05/token-count-for-lp-presidential-candidates/|title=Token count for LP presidential candidates|date=May 4, 2012|website=Independentpoliticalreport.com|accessdate=June 25, 2016}}</ref> {{Unreliable source?|sure=y|reason=News aggregator with no editorial policy.|date=September 2019}} <ref>http://www.jasonpye.com/2012/05/brief-recap-of-the-libertarian-national-convention/</ref>\n\n==Convention speakers==\nSpeakers at the convention included:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertywillwin.com/speakers|title=Liberty Will Win \u2013 Libertarian Party Information|website=Libertywillwin.com|accessdate=June 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104191315/http://www.libertywillwin.com/speakers|archive-date=November 4, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Norma Jean Almodovar]] \u2013 [[Sex worker]] activist and former LAPD cop, LP candidate for [[Lieutenant Governor of California]]\n* [[David Bergland]] \u2013 [[1984 United States presidential election|1984]] LP presidential nominee\n* Judge John Buttrick \u2013 Superior Court Judge of [[Maricopa County, Arizona]]\n* Alicia Garcia Clark \u2013 National [[Libertarian National Committee]] (LNC) leader from 1981 to 1983\n* [[Ed Clark]] \u2013 [[1980 United States presidential election|1980]] LP presidential nominee\n* Michael Cloud \u2013 Author, ''Secrets of Libertarian Persuasion'', who ran for [[U.S. Senate]] in [[Massachusetts]] in 2002\n* [[Sharon Harris]] \u2013 President of [[Advocates for Self-Government]]\n* [[Carla Howell]] \u2013 [[Executive Director]] of the Libertarian Party; 2000 LP nominee for the U.S Senate in Massachusetts, 2002 LP nominee for [[Governor of Massachusetts]]\n* [[Manny Klausner]] \u2013 Co-founder of the [[Reason Foundation]], and former editor of ''Reason'' magazine\n* [[Nancy Lord]] \u2013 [[1992 United States presidential election|1992]] LP vice-presidential nominee\n* [[Tibor R. Machan|Tibor Machan]] \u2013 Professor of [[philosophy]] at [[Auburn University]]\n* [[Tonie Nathan]] \u2013 [[1972 United States presidential election|1972]] LP vice-presidential nominee, and first woman in U.S. History to receive an [[Electoral College (United States)|electoral vote]]\n* [[Reason Foundation|Robert Poole]] \u2013 Co-founder of ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' magazine\n* [[Mary Ruwart]] \u2013 Research scientist and former contender for the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]] presidential nomination\n{{clear}}\n\n==Presidential candidates==\n\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" | Libertarian Party presidential candidates, 2012\n|- \n!class=\"unsortable\"| \n!text-align:center width:120px; \"|Candidate\n!|'''Home state'''\n! style=\"width:300px;\"  class=\"unsortable\"|Profession\n! class=\"unsortable\"|Campaign\n|-\n!align=center|[[File:Blank.png|100x100px]]\n!data-sort-value=\"Burns, Jim\"|'''Jim Burns'''\n| [[Nevada]]\n|\n|\n|-